Movie: Whistle and I'll Come to You

Review: Yeah, probably is as bad as they say. A few questionable changes from the novel and generally just can't really sell the story. To its credit though, it does have the feel and vibe that an Ellroy adaptation should at times, and I think Aaron Eckhart is a good Lee Blanchard, at least in the way he looks and carries himself. It's never really boring either, but just a bit of a miss.

The one part of the extended ballet sequence, where Vicky is moving through the various backgrounds and dances and floats through this dreamy place that looks like some other world is so good. Had me smiling and thinking, damn, that's the movies

An odd one. Has a really surprising sense of humour to it, mostly in Mr Dean's antics and his character in general. But it's one of those ones where I do think I'm missing what makes it so revered. Obviously it looks great, and there's some beautiful scenes. Everyone talks about the matte painted backdrops for good reason, but the one scene where Joseph Anthony brings Sister Ruth a glass of milk at the quiet dawn was really atmospheric and strikingly lit and sticks in my mind. Generally though, just "alright" for me

Follows the rule that the best noirs have voice-overs. The stats don't lie, baby. Pretty tense in parts, like the scene where Keyes shows up at Jeff's apartment, and often quite funny. It strikes me after reading other reviews the cool sort of dreamy way the film portrays Neff's loneliness and boredom, standing looking out the window smoking, going bowling solo. No wonder he got sucked into Phyllis' scheme

Plays like a comedy more than I expected even given the other reviews that say the same. Not a fan of weird horny Napoleon. Get rid. Waterloo was easily the best sequence, so it's a shame we didn't get more battle scenes, but I suppose that's a different film. At times I found myself wishing I was watching the Bondarchuk Waterloo. It did put me in the mood to read War and Peace at some point then watch Bondarchuk's version of that. Altogether, a decent Friday night cinema watch

Did like this, but it continues the pattern of me not being struck very deeply by the big classic noirs. I did like how the tone of this one starts out being fairly playful and good-humoured, and just gets gradually darker...probably the turning point is Scary Bogey describing the sicko fantasy of strangling a girl while gets this big nasty toothy grin on his face. Very memorable ending

Considering this is Fritz Lang, and it's one of "the" film noirs, I found this slightly underwhelming compared to its massive reputation. Certainly does have some pretty hard hitting moments, and a great gallery of bad blokes epitomised of course in Lee Marvin, and it is a joy to watch Glenn Ford walk around a punch up a few scumbags. But I think compared to the heights of something like Detour, this one just falls a bit flat.

It must be both a lot easier and a lot harder to be a hitman in the age of Amazon Prime, WeWork and Google Maps...thought this was great, tight, gripping and really funny. That fight scene with the big guy in Florida, woof!
The bride in her brief appearance in the film is just absolutely otherworldly. What an impression to make in about 5 mins or so of screen time
It's alright. Often plays like a comedy, though it does have "scary" or threatening scenes. Just slightly on the boring side despite its runtime
